> But what happens if you just disable `black-background`? Doesn't that have the same effect?

With `black-background` disabled I always get `[0x559874307320] 🗙 Non-opaque texture (1280x720) below` even when the window is full-screened (no clipping). 


With this hacky patch that reduces the Viewfinder widget to the size of the video you can see, that when ever the rounded corners of the window aren't clipping the video, offloading works. You may need to resize the window to make sure that the corners don't overlap the video.
```
diff --git a/aperture/src/viewfinder.rs b/aperture/src/viewfinder.rs
index 8c42a31..48a53f9 100644
--- a/aperture/src/viewfinder.rs
+++ b/aperture/src/viewfinder.rs
@@ -281,13 +281,17 @@ mod imp {

             self.picture
                 .set_accessible_role(gtk::AccessibleRole::Presentation);
-            self.picture.set_hexpand(true);
-            self.picture.set_vexpand(true);
             self.picture.set_paintable(Some(&paintable));

             self.offload.set_child(Some(&self.picture));
             self.offload.set_parent(&*obj);
             self.offload.set_black_background(true);
+            // Setting HALGIN to center on the offload doesn't work
+            //ideally we force the size of gtk::picture to always respect the ratio
+            obj.set_halign (gtk::Align::Center);
+            obj.set_hexpand(false);
+            obj.set_vexpand(false);
+            self.offload.set_valign (gtk::Align::Center);

             self.tee.set(tee).unwrap();

```

